docstrings: * Starts up the presentation if the client is capable.

* Inspect the client to see what it's capable of, this
	 * should only happens once per runtime.

* Loads the dependencies of reveal.js. Dependencies are
     * defined via the configuration option 'dependencies'
     * and will be loaded prior to starting/binding reveal.js.
     * Some dependencies may have an 'async' flag, if so they
     * will load after reveal.js has been started up.

* Starts up reveal.js by binding input events and navigating
	 * to the current URL deeplink if there is one.

* Finds and stores references to DOM elements which are
	 * required by the presentation. If a required element is
	 * not found, it is created.

* Creates a hidden div with role aria-live to announce the
	 * current slide content. Hide the div off-screen to make it
	 * available only to Assistive Technologies.

* Configures the presentation for printing to a static
	 * PDF.

* This is an unfortunate necessity. Iframes can trigger the
	 * parent window to scroll, for example by focusing an input.
	 * This scrolling can not be prevented by hiding overflow in
	 * CSS so we have to resort to repeatedly checking if the
	 * browser has decided to offset our slides :(

* Creates an HTML element and returns a reference to it.
	 * If the element already exists the existing instance will
	 * be returned.

* Creates the slide background elements and appends them
	 * to the background container. One element is created per
	 * slide no matter if the given slide has visible background.

* Creates a background for the given slide.
	 *
	 * @param {HTMLElement} slide
	 * @param {HTMLElement} container The element that the background
	 * should be appended to

* Registers a listener to postMessage events, this makes it
	 * possible to call all reveal.js API methods from another
	 * window. For example:
	 *
	 * revealWindow.postMessage( JSON.stringify({
	 *   method: 'slide',
	 *   args: [ 2 ]
	 * }), '*' );

* Applies the configuration settings from the config
	 * object. May be called multiple times.
* Binds all event listeners.
* Unbinds all event listeners.

* Extend object a with the properties of object b.
	 * If there's a conflict, object b takes precedence.
* Converts the target object to an array.
* Utility for deserializing a value.

* Measures the distance in pixels between point a
	 * and point b.
	 *
	 * @param {Object} a point with x/y properties
	 * @param {Object} b point with x/y properties
* Applies a CSS transform to the target element.

* Applies CSS transforms to the slides container. The container
	 * is transformed from two separate sources: layout and the overview
	 * mode.
* Injects the given CSS styles into the DOM.

* Converts various color input formats to an {r:0,g:0,b:0} object.
	 *
	 * @param {String} color The string representation of a color,
	 * the following formats are supported:
	 * - #000
	 * - #000000
	 * - rgb(0,0,0)

* Calculates brightness on a scale of 0-255.
	 *
	 * @param color See colorStringToRgb for supported formats.

* Retrieves the height of the given element by looking
	 * at the position and height of its immediate children.

* Returns the remaining height within the parent of the
	 * target element.
	 *
	 * remaining height = [ configured parent height ] - [ current parent height ]
* Checks if this instance is being used to print a PDF.
* Hides the address bar if we're on a mobile device.

* Causes the address bar to hide on mobile devices,
	 * more vertical space ftw.

* Dispatches an event of the specified type from the
	 * reveal DOM element.
* Wrap all links in 3D goodness.
* Unwrap all 3D links.
* Bind preview frame links.
* Unbind preview frame links.
* Opens a preview window for the target URL.
* Opens a overlay window with help material.
* Closes any currently open overlay.

* Applies JavaScript-controlled layout rules to the
	 * presentation.

* Applies layout logic to the contents of all slides in
	 * the presentation.

* Calculates the computed pixel size of our slides. These
	 * values are based on the width and height configuration
	 * options.

* Stores the vertical index of a stack so that the same
	 * vertical slide can be selected when navigating to and
	 * from the stack.

* Moves the overview viewport to the current slides.

* Return a sorted fragments list, ordered by an increasing
	 * "data-fragment-index" attribute.
	 *
	 * Fragments will be revealed in the order that they are returned by
	 * this function, so you can use the index attributes to control the
	 * order of fragment appearance.
	 *
	 * To maintain a sensible default fragment order, fragments are presumed
	 * to be passed in document order. This function adds a "fragment-index"
	 * attribute to each node if such an attribute is not already present,
	 * and sets that attribute to an integer value which is the position of
	 * the fragment within the fragments list.
